      "solution": "import java.util.*;\nclass Solution{\n  public static void main(String[] a){\n    String s=new Scanner(System.in).next();\n    int n=s.length(), l=(n-1)/2, r=l+1;\n    StringBuilder out=new StringBuilder().append(s.charAt(l));\n    while(out.length()<n){ if(r<n) out.append(s.charAt(r++)); if(--l>=0) out.append(s.charAt(l)); }\n    System.out.println(out);\n  }\n}\n",
      "statement": "You are given a word [[S]].\nBuild a new word in middle-out order:\n\nFor odd-length strings, take the middle letter first.\n\nFor even-length strings, take the left middle letter first.\n\nAfter the initial pick, always take letters alternately FROM the right side and FROM the left side until all letters are used.\n\nCase is preserved.\n\n<<Examples>>\n\n<<Input>>\nABCDE\n<<Output>>\nCDBEA\n(odd: middle C, then right D, left B, right E, left A)\n\n<<Input>>\nwxyz\n<<Output>>\nxywz \n(even: left-middle x, then right y, then left w, then right z → xywz)",
